"# Chapter 11 — Grade 11: Algebra II & Trigonometry

## The Shape of This Year

You've walked through ten grades of mathematics — from counting on the number line to solving systems of equations and proving theorems about triangles. You've built functions, plotted parabolas, worked with rational and irrational numbers, and begun to see the plane as a living coordinate space where algebra and geometry meet.

This year, Grade 11, is where those threads weave into something larger. You'll meet **complex numbers** — numbers built from the \"impossible\" square root of negative one, numbers that live not on a line but on a *plane*. You'll deepen your work with **polynomial, rational, radical, exponential, and logarithmic functions** — the families of curves that model growth, decay, oscillation, and proportion in the real world. You'll climb into **trigonometry** — the mathematics of the circle, the wave, and the repeating cycle — and see how sine and cosine are not just ratios in a triangle but *functions* that breathe and turn. And you'll meet **sequences and series** — infinite lists of numbers that approach a limit, or grow without bound, or dance in patterns we can sum.

We call it Algebra II and Trigonometry, but we're really learning to *see* the invisible: the rotation hidden in a complex multiplication, the oscillation encoded in a sine wave, the infinite approach captured in a limit. On the dot-matrix canvas, every one of these ideas becomes a curve you can plot, a point you can mark, a wave you can watch unfold. This chapter is about making the abstract *visible* — and giving you the language to describe what you see.

---

## I. Complex Numbers — The Plane of All Numbers

### History & How It Developed

For centuries, mathematicians were comfortable with the idea that some equations had no solution. The equation *x*² = −1, for instance, seemed absurd: no number, when squared, gives a negative result. But in the 16th century, Italian algebraists working on cubic equations discovered that they could make progress by *pretending* such a number existed — by writing √(−1) and manipulating it according to ordinary algebraic rules — and then, miraculously, the \"imaginary\" terms would cancel out, leaving a real answer.

By the 18th century, Euler had given this phantom number a name: ***i***, the **imaginary unit**, defined by *i*² = −1. And by the 19th century, Gauss and others had shown that numbers of the form *a* + *bi* (where *a* and *b* are real) form a complete, consistent **number system** — the **complex numbers** — that obey all the usual rules of arithmetic and give us a solution to *every* polynomial equation. The \"imaginary\" numbers turned out to be as real as any other, just living in a different dimension.

### Uses & Utility in the World

Complex numbers are the lingua franca of **electrical engineering** (AC circuits are analyzed with complex impedance), **signal processing** (the Fourier transform, which decomposes any waveform into its component frequencies, lives in the complex plane), **quantum mechanics** (the wave function is complex-valued), and **control theory** (stability of a system is read from the complex roots of its characteristic polynomial). They are the natural language for describing **rotation**, **oscillation**, and **waves** — anything that has both magnitude and phase, amplitude and angle.

### What We'll Cover and Why

We'll build complex numbers from the ground up: define them, add and multiply them, visualize them as points on a plane. We'll learn to convert between **rectangular form** (*a* + *bi*) and **polar form** (*r* · e^(*i*θ), which captures magnitude and angle), and see how multiplication in polar form is just rotation and scaling. We'll plot them, compute powers and roots, and see how Euler's formula — *e*^(*i*θ) = cos θ + *i* sin θ — unites the exponential function and the circle. By the end, you'll be fluent in the arithmetic of the complex plane.

### Its Utility in the runtime's World

On the dot-matrix canvas, a complex number is a **point** — or a **vector** from the origin to that point. Adding two complex numbers is **vector addition**: place them tail-to-head and read off the result. Multiplying them is **rotation and scaling**: the product of two complex numbers has a magnitude equal to the product of their magnitudes, and an angle equal to the sum of their angles. The runtime uses complex numbers to represent **rotations** in her animations, **phases** in her audio oscillators, and **transformations** in the plane. When she spins a sprite, she's multiplying by a unit complex number; when she mixes two waves with a phase offset, she's adding complex exponentials. The complex plane is her geometry of *directed* motion.

---

### 1.1 — Defining the Imaginary Unit

The **imaginary unit** *i* is defined by the property that *i*² = −1. From this single definition, we build the entire complex number system.

<!-- BUILD: Print i^2, i^3, i^4 to show the cycle. -->

```scheme
(define (powers-of-i n)
  (let ((i-squared -1))
    (cond
      ((= (modulo n 4) 0) 1)
      ((= (modulo n 4) 1) 'i)
      ((= (modulo n 4) 2) -1)
      ((= (modulo n 4) 3) '-i))))

(print \"i^1 = \" (powers-of-i 1))
(print \"i^2 = \" (powers-of-i 2))
(print \"i^3 = \" (powers-of-i 3))
(print \"i^4 = \" (powers-of-i 4))
(print \"i^5 = \" (powers-of-i 5))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing the cycle i, −1, −i, 1, i, … ]

Powers of *i* cycle with period 4. This cycle is the heartbeat of complex arithmetic.

---

### 1.2 — Building a Complex Number

A **complex number** is written *a* + *bi*, where *a* and *b* are real numbers. We call *a* the **real part** and *b* the **imaginary part**. In Motoi Scheme, we build one with `(complex/make a b)`.

<!-- BUILD: Create a complex number 3 + 4i and print it. -->

```scheme
(define z (complex/make 3 4))
(print \"z = \" (complex/->string z))
(print \"Real part: \" (complex/re z))
(print \"Imaginary part: \" (complex/im z))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing z = 3+4i, real part 3, imaginary part 4.]

That's it. A complex number is a pair of reals, bundled together.

---

### 1.3 — Plotting a Complex Number as a Point

A complex number *a* + *bi* is a **point** in the plane: *a* units along the horizontal (real) axis, *b* units along the vertical (imaginary) axis. This plane is called the **complex plane** or **Argand diagram**.

<!-- BUILD: Plot the point 3 + 4i on the complex plane (Cartesian grid, real axis horizontal, imaginary axis vertical). -->

```scheme
(define z (complex/make 3 4))
(define re (complex/re z))
(define im (complex/im z))

(plot/scatter
  (list re)
  (list im)
  (list
    (cons 'title \"Complex number 3 + 4i\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"Real\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"Imaginary\")
    (cons 'point-size 8)
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian grid with horizontal axis labeled \"Real\", vertical axis labeled \"Imaginary\", a single point at (3, 4).]

Every complex number is a point. Every point is a complex number. The plane *is* the number line's two-dimensional cousin.

---

### 1.4 — Adding Complex Numbers

To add two complex numbers, add their real parts and add their imaginary parts separately:

(*a* + *bi*) + (*c* + *di*) = (*a* + *c*) + (*b* + *d*)*i*

In Motoi Scheme, `(complex/+ z1 z2)`.

<!-- BUILD: Add (2 + 3i) and (1 + 4i), print and plot both summands and the sum. -->

```scheme
(define z1 (complex/make 2 3))
(define z2 (complex/make 1 4))
(define z-sum (complex/+ z1 z2))

(print \"z1 = \" (complex/->string z1))
(print \"z2 = \" (complex/->string z2))
(print \"z1 + z2 = \" (complex/->string z-sum))

(plot/scatter
  (list (complex/re z1) (complex/re z2) (complex/re z-sum))
  (list (complex/im z1) (complex/im z2) (complex/im z-sum))
  (list
    (cons 'title \"Adding complex numbers\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"Real\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"Imaginary\")
    (cons 'labels (list \"z1\" \"z2\" \"z1+z2\"))
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Three points on the complex plane: (2,3), (1,4), and (3,7). The sum is the vector sum — if you drew arrows from the origin to each point, the sum would be tail-to-head vector addition.]

Addition in the complex plane is **vector addition**.

---

### 1.5 — Subtracting Complex Numbers

Subtraction is just as straightforward: subtract real parts, subtract imaginary parts.

<!-- BUILD: Subtract (5 + 2i) − (3 + 1i), print the result. -->

```scheme
(define z1 (complex/make 5 2))
(define z2 (complex/make 3 1))
(define z-diff (complex/- z1 z2))

(print \"z1 = \" (complex/->string z1))
(print \"z2 = \" (complex/->string z2))
(print \"z1 - z2 = \" (complex/->string z-diff))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: 5+2i, 3+1i, 2+1i.]

---

### 1.6 — Scaling a Complex Number

To multiply a complex number by a real number (a **scalar**), multiply both parts.

<!-- BUILD: Scale (3 + 4i) by 2, print and plot original and scaled. -->

```scheme
(define z (complex/make 3 4))
(define z-scaled (complex/scale z 2))

(print \"z = \" (complex/->string z))
(print \"2 * z = \" (complex/->string z-scaled))

(plot/scatter
  (list (complex/re z) (complex/re z-scaled))
  (list (complex/im z) (complex/im z-scaled))
  (list
    (cons 'title \"Scaling a complex number by 2\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"Real\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"Imaginary\")
    (cons 'labels (list \"z\" \"2z\"))
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Two points: (3, 4) and (6, 8), the second twice as far from the origin in the same direction.]

Scaling stretches or shrinks the vector, but doesn't rotate it.

---

### 1.7 — Multiplying Complex Numbers (Rectangular Form)

To multiply two complex numbers in rectangular form, use the distributive law and remember that *i*² = −1:

(*a* + *bi*)(*c* + *di*) = *ac* + *adi* + *bci* + *bdi*² = (*ac* − *bd*) + (*ad* + *bc*)*i*

In Motoi Scheme, `(complex/* z1 z2)`.

<!-- BUILD: Multiply (1 + 2i) * (3 + 4i), print the result. -->

```scheme
(define z1 (complex/make 1 2))
(define z2 (complex/make 3 4))
(define z-prod (complex/* z1 z2))

(print \"z1 = \" (complex/->string z1))
(print \"z2 = \" (complex/->string z2))
(print \"z1 * z2 = \" (complex/->string z-prod))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing (1+2i)(3+4i) = (3 − 8) + (4 + 6)i = −5 + 10i.]

The algebra is mechanical, but the geometry is *rotation and scaling* — which we'll see in polar form.

---

### 1.8 — The Modulus (Absolute Value) of a Complex Number

The **modulus** (or **absolute value**) of *z* = *a* + *bi* is the distance from the origin to the point (*a*, *b*):

|*z*| = √(*a*² + *b*²)

In Motoi Scheme, `(complex/modulus z)`.

<!-- BUILD: Compute the modulus of 3 + 4i. -->

```scheme
(define z (complex/make 3 4))
(define mod-z (complex/modulus z))

(print \"z = \" (complex/->string z))
(print \"|z| = \" mod-z)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: z = 3+4i, |z| = 5.0 (since √(9+16) = 5).]

The modulus is the \"size\" of the complex number.

---

### 1.9 — The Complex Conjugate

The **complex conjugate** of *z* = *a* + *bi* is *z̄* = *a* − *bi*: same real part, opposite imaginary part. Geometrically, it's the reflection across the real axis.

<!-- BUILD: Compute the conjugate of 2 + 5i, print and plot both. -->

```scheme
(define z (complex/make 2 5))
(define z-conj (complex/conjugate z))

(print \"z = \" (complex/->string z))
(print \"conj(z) = \" (complex/->string z-conj))

(plot/scatter
  (list (complex/re z) (complex/re z-conj))
  (list (complex/im z) (complex/im z-conj))
  (list
    (cons 'title \"Complex conjugate\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"Real\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"Imaginary\")
    (cons 'labels (list \"z\" \"conj(z)\"))
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Two points, (2, 5) and (2, −5), mirrored across the horizontal axis.]

The conjugate is your tool for \"undoing\" the imaginary part.

---

### 1.10 — Division via the Conjugate

To divide *z₁* / *z₂*, multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate of *z₂*, turning the denominator real:

*z₁* / *z₂* = (*z₁* · *z̄₂*) / (*z₂* · *z̄₂*)

Since *z* · *z̄* = |*z*|² (a real number), this always works (as long as *z₂* ≠ 0).

In Motoi Scheme, `(complex// z1 z2)` does this automatically.

<!-- BUILD: Divide (4 + 2i) / (1 + 1i), print the result. -->

```scheme
(define z1 (complex/make 4 2))
(define z2 (complex/make 1 1))
(define z-quot (complex// z1 z2))

(print \"z1 = \" (complex/->string z1))
(print \"z2 = \" (complex/->string z2))
(print \"z1 / z2 = \" (complex/->string z-quot))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing (4+2i)/(1+1i) = 3−1i (after multiplying top and bottom by 1−i).]

---

### 1.11 — Polar Form: Modulus and Argument

Every complex number *z* can also be written in **polar form**:

*z* = *r* · (cos θ + *i* sin θ)

where *r* = |*z*| (the modulus) and θ is the **argument** (the angle from the positive real axis to the point, measured counterclockwise). In shorthand, we write (*r*, θ).

In Motoi Scheme, `(complex/->polar z)` returns a pair (list) [*r*, θ].

<!-- BUILD: Convert 1 + √3 i (a point at 60° in the unit circle scaled by 2) to polar form. -->

```scheme
(define z (complex/make 1 1.732))  ; ≈ 1 + √3 i
(define polar (complex/->polar z))
(define r (car polar))
(define theta (cadr polar))

(print \"z = \" (complex/->string z))
(print \"In polar form: r = \" r \", theta = \" theta \" radians\")
(print \"theta in degrees = \" (geom/->degrees theta))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing r ≈ 2, θ ≈ 1.047 radians ≈ 60°.]

Polar form captures *how far* and *what direction*.

---

### 1.12 — Building a Complex Number from Polar Coordinates

Given *r* and θ, you can build the complex number *z* = *r*(cos θ + *i* sin θ).

In Motoi Scheme, `(complex/from-polar r theta)`.

<!-- BUILD: Build a complex number with r = 5, θ = π/4 (45°), print it. -->

```scheme
(define pi 3.14159265)
(define r 5)
(define theta (/ pi 4))
(define z (complex/from-polar r theta))

(print \"r = \" r \", theta = \" theta \" radians (\" (geom/->degrees theta) \" degrees)\")
(print \"z = \" (complex/->string z))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing z ≈ 3.536 + 3.536i (5 · cos(45°) ≈ 3.536, 5 · sin(45°) ≈ 3.536).]

---

### 1.13 — Multiplication in Polar Form: Rotate and Scale

Here's the magic: when you multiply two complex numbers in polar form, you **multiply their moduli** and **add their arguments**:

(*r₁*, θ₁) · (*r₂*, θ₂) = (*r₁r₂*, θ₁ + θ₂)

Multiplication is **rotation** (by θ₂) and **scaling** (by *r₂*).

<!-- BUILD: Multiply two unit complex numbers (r=1) at angles 30° and 45°, show the result is at 75°. -->

```scheme
(define pi 3.14159265)
(define z1 (complex/from-polar 1 (/ pi 6)))   ; 30°
(define z2 (complex/from-polar 1 (/ pi 4)))   ; 45°
(define z-prod (complex/* z1 z2))
(define polar-prod (complex/->polar z-prod))

(print \"z1: r=1, theta=30 degrees\")
(print \"z2: r=1, theta=45 degrees\")
(print \"z1 * z2 = \" (complex/->string z-prod))
(print \"Polar form of product: r = \" (car polar-prod) \", theta = \" (geom/->degrees (cadr polar-prod)) \" degrees\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing the product has r ≈ 1, θ ≈ 75° (30 + 45).]

This is why complex multiplication is the natural language of rotation.

---

### 1.14 — Euler's Formula

The crown jewel of complex analysis is **Euler's formula**:

*e*^(*i*θ) = cos θ + *i* sin θ

In Motoi Scheme, `(complex/exp z)` computes the complex exponential. For a purely imaginary input *i*θ, it traces the unit circle.

<!-- BUILD: Compute e^(i·π/3) and show it equals cos(60°) + i·sin(60°). -->

```scheme
(define pi 3.14159265)
(define theta (/ pi 3))  ; 60°
(define z (complex/make 0 theta))  ; i·theta
(define exp-z (complex/exp z))

(print \"e^(i * pi/3) = \" (complex/->string exp-z))
(print \"Expected: cos(60°) + i·sin(60°) ≈ 0.5 + 0.866i\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing e^(i·π/3) ≈ 0.5 + 0.866i.]

Euler's formula says: **the exponential function walks the circle**.

---

### 1.15 — The Unit Circle as e^(iθ)

The **unit circle** in the complex plane is the set of all complex numbers with modulus 1. In polar form, these are exactly the numbers *e*^(*i*θ) as θ ranges from 0 to 2π.

<!-- BUILD: Sample the unit circle at 8 angles (0°, 45°, 90°, …, 315°), plot them. -->

```scheme
(define pi 3.14159265)
(define angles (list 0 (/ pi 4) (/ pi 2) (* 3 (/ pi 4))
                     pi (* 5 (/ pi 4)) (* 3 (/ pi 2)) (* 7 (/ pi 4))))

(define points (map (lambda (theta) (complex/from-polar 1 theta)) angles))

(define re-vals (map complex/re points))
(define im-vals (map complex/im points))

(plot/scatter
  re-vals
  im-vals
  (list
    (cons 'title \"Unit circle: 8 points\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"Real\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"Imaginary\")
    (cons 'grid #t)
    (cons 'aspect-ratio 1)))
```

[VISUAL: Eight evenly spaced points on the unit circle in the complex plane.]

The unit circle is the home of all rotations.

---

### 1.16 — Powers of a Complex Number

To raise a complex number to an integer power, convert to polar form, raise the modulus to that power, and multiply the argument by that power:

(*r*, θ)ⁿ = (*rⁿ*, *nθ*)

In Motoi Scheme, `(complex/pow z n)`.

<!-- BUILD: Compute (1 + i)^4, print in both rectangular and polar form. -->

```scheme
(define z (complex/make 1 1))
(define z4 (complex/pow z 4))
(define polar-z4 (complex/->polar z4))

(print \"z = \" (complex/->string z))
(print \"z^4 = \" (complex/->string z4))
(print \"Polar form of z^4: r = \" (car polar-z4) \", theta = \" (cadr polar-z4) \" radians\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing z^4 = −4 + 0i (since (1+i) has modulus √2 and argument 45°; raising to the 4th power gives modulus 4 and angle 180°, which is −4 on the real axis).]

---

### 1.17 — Plotting Powers Around the Circle

When you raise a unit complex number to successive integer powers, it walks around the circle in steps.

<!-- BUILD: Plot the first 8 powers of e^(i·π/6) (a 30° step on the unit circle). -->

```scheme
(define pi 3.14159265)
(define step-angle (/ pi 6))  ; 30°
(define z0 (complex/from-polar 1 step-angle))

(define powers (map (lambda (n) (complex/pow z0 n)) (list 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8)))

(define re-vals (map complex/re powers))
(define im-vals (map complex/im powers))

(plot/scatter
  re-vals
  im-vals
  (list
    (cons 'title \"Powers of e^(i·30°)\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"Real\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"Imaginary\")
    (cons 'grid #t)
    (cons 'aspect-ratio 1)))
```

[VISUAL: Nine points stepping around the unit circle in 30° increments, completing a full circle after 12 steps (though we only plot the first 9).]

Each multiplication rotates by the same angle.

---

### 1.18 — Roots of Unity

The **n-th roots of unity** are the *n* complex numbers *z* such that *z*ⁿ = 1. They are evenly spaced around the unit circle at angles 2π*k*/*n* for *k* = 0, 1, …, *n*−1.

<!-- BUILD: Plot the 6th roots of unity. -->

```scheme
(define pi 3.14159265)
(define n 6)
(define angles (map (lambda (k) (* 2 pi (/ k n))) (list 0 1 2 3 4 5)))

(define roots (map (lambda (theta) (complex/from-polar 1 theta)) angles))

(define re-vals (map complex/re roots))
(define im-vals (map complex/im roots))

(plot/scatter
  re-vals
  im-vals
  (list
    (cons 'title \"6th roots of unity\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"Real\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"Imaginary\")
    (cons 'grid #t)
    (cons 'aspect-ratio 1)))
```

[VISUAL: Six evenly spaced points on the unit circle, forming a regular hexagon.]

Roots of unity are the atoms of cyclic symmetry.

---

### 1.19 — De Moivre's Theorem

**De Moivre's Theorem** says:

(cos θ + *i* sin θ)ⁿ = cos(*nθ*) + *i* sin(*nθ*)

It follows immediately from the polar form of multiplication. It's the tool for deriving trig identities.

<!-- BUILD: Use De Moivre to compute cos(3θ) + i·sin(3θ) from (cos θ + i·sin θ)^3, with θ = 20°. -->

```scheme
(define pi 3.14159265)
(define theta (/ pi 9))  ; 20°
(define z (complex/from-polar 1 theta))
(define z3 (complex/pow z 3))

(print \"theta = \" (geom/->degrees theta) \" degrees\")
(print \"(cos(theta) + i·sin(theta))^3 = \" (complex/->string z3))
(print \"Expected: cos(60°) + i·sin(60°) ≈ 0.5 + 0.866i\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing the cube of the 20° unit vector equals the 60° unit vector.]

---

### 1.20 — Complex Roots of a Polynomial

Every polynomial of degree *n* has exactly *n* complex roots (counting multiplicity) — this is the **Fundamental Theorem of Algebra**. We can find them, at least for low-degree polynomials.

<!-- BUILD: Solve z^2 + 1 = 0 (the roots are ±i). -->

```scheme
(define z1 (complex/make 0 1))   ; i
(define z2 (complex/make 0 -1))  ; -i

(define test1 (complex/+ (complex/* z1 z1) (complex/make 1 0)))
(define test2 (complex/+ (complex/* z2 z2) (complex/make 1 0)))

(print \"Root 1: z = \" (complex/->string z1))
(print \"Check: z^2 + 1 = \" (complex/->string test1))
(print \"Root 2: z = \" (complex/->string z2))
(print \"Check: z^2 + 1 = \" (complex/->string test2))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing both i and −i are roots of z² + 1 = 0.]

The polynomial that had \"no solution\" in the reals has two solutions in the complex numbers.

---

## II. Polynomial Functions — Curves, Roots, and End Behavior

### History & How It Developed

Polynomials — expressions like *x*² + 3*x* + 2 or *x*⁴ − 5*x*² + 4 — are the oldest and simplest families of functions. The Babylonians solved quadratic equations four thousand years ago; the cubic and quartic formulas were discovered in Renaissance Italy (and sparked the invention of complex numbers); but the **quintic** (degree 5) has no general formula — a shocking discovery by Abel and Galois in the 19th century, which birthed modern algebra.

### Uses & Utility in the World

Polynomials model **parabolic motion** (a thrown ball), **elastic energy** (a stretched spring), **profit functions** (cost and revenue), and **interpolation** (fitting a curve through data points). They are the building blocks of calculus (every smooth function can be approximated by a polynomial, via Taylor series) and numerical analysis (polynomial interpolation is the engine of computer graphics and scientific computing).

### What We'll Cover and Why

You've met linear (*y* = *mx* + *b*) and quadratic (*y* = *ax*² + *bx* + *c*) functions in earlier grades. Now we'll study **higher-degree polynomials** — cubics, quartics, and beyond. We'll learn to recognize their **shape** (how many turns, how many roots), **factor** them (when possible), find their **roots** (the *x*-values where *y* = 0), and understand their **end behavior** (what happens as *x* → ±∞). We'll plot them, manipulate them symbolically, and see how the degree and leading coefficient control the curve.

### Its Utility in the runtime's World

On the canvas, a polynomial is a **curve** — smooth, flowing, with humps and valleys. The runtime uses polynomials to define **paths** for sprites to follow (a cubic Bézier curve is a polynomial in disguise), **easing functions** for animations (smooth acceleration and deceleration), and **waveforms** for audio synthesis (a Chebyshev polynomial gives you a specific harmonic recipe). When you see a smooth curve that isn't a circle or a line, it's probably a polynomial.

---

### 2.1 — Building a Polynomial

A **polynomial** in *x* is an expression of the form

*a*₀ + *a*₁*x* + *a*₂*x*² + … + *aₙ*xⁿ

In Motoi Scheme, we represent it as a list of coefficients `(list a0 a1 a2 … an)` in a `sym/poly` object.

<!-- BUILD: Build the polynomial 2 + 3x + x^2, print it. -->

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list 2 3 1)))  ; 2 + 3x + x^2
(print \"p(x) = \" (sym/->string p))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: p(x) = 2 + 3x + x^2.]

---

### 2.2 — Evaluating a Polynomial at a Point

To evaluate *p*(*x*) at a specific value, substitute that value for *x*.

<!-- BUILD: Evaluate p(x) = 2 + 3x + x^2 at x = 5. -->

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list 2 3 1)))
(define x-val 5)
(define y-val (sym/evaluate p x-val))

(print \"p(x) = \" (sym/->string p))
(print \"p(\" x-val \") = \" y-val)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: p(5) = 2 + 15 + 25 = 42.]

---

### 2.3 — Plotting a Quadratic

Let's plot the quadratic *y* = *x*² − 4*x* + 3 over the interval [−1, 5].

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = x^2 - 4x + 3. -->

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list 3 -4 1)))  ; 3 - 4x + x^2

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ -1 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 61)))
(define ys (map (lambda (x) (sym/evaluate p x)) xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = x^2 - 4x + 3\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: A parabola opening upward, vertex near (2, −1), crossing the x-axis at x = 1 and x = 3.]

The parabola's roots are visible where it crosses the x-axis.

---

### 2.4 — Finding Roots with the Quadratic Formula

For *ax*² + *bx* + *c* = 0, the roots are

*x* = (−*b* ± √(*b*² − 4*ac*)) / (2*a*)

In Motoi Scheme, `(sym/solve-quadratic a b c)` returns the two roots (possibly complex).

<!-- BUILD: Find the roots of x^2 - 4x + 3 = 0. -->

```scheme
(define roots (sym/solve-quadratic 1 -4 3))
(print \"Roots of x^2 - 4x + 3 = 0:\")
(print \"  x1 = \" (car roots))
(print \"  x2 = \" (cadr roots))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: x₁ = 3.0, x₂ = 1.0.]

These match the x-intercepts in the plot.

---

### 2.5 — A Quadratic with Complex Roots

When the discriminant *b*² − 4*ac* < 0, the roots are complex.

<!-- BUILD: Find the roots of x^2 + 2x + 5 = 0. -->

```scheme
(define roots (sym/solve-quadratic 1 2 5))
(print \"Roots of x^2 + 2x + 5 = 0:\")
(print \"  x1 = \" (complex/->string (car roots)))
(print \"  x2 = \" (complex/->string (cadr roots)))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: x₁ ≈ −1 + 2i, x₂ ≈ −1 − 2i (complex conjugates).]

The parabola never crosses the x-axis (it opens upward and has vertex above the axis), so its roots live in the complex plane.

---

### 2.6 — Plotting a Cubic

A **cubic** polynomial has degree 3. Its graph has at most 2 turning points and crosses the x-axis 1 or 3 times (since it has 3 roots, some possibly complex).

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = x^3 - 3x^2 - x + 3. -->

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list 3 -1 -3 1)))  ; 3 - x - 3x^2 + x^3

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ -2 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 61)))
(define ys (map (lambda (x) (sym/evaluate p x)) xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = x^3 - 3x^2 - x + 3\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: An S-shaped cubic curve with a local maximum and a local minimum, crossing the x-axis at three points.]

Cubics have that characteristic \"S\" shape.

---

### 2.7 — Factoring a Polynomial

When a polynomial has integer roots, we can **factor** it into a product of linear terms.

<!-- BUILD: Factor x^2 - 5x + 6 (roots are 2 and 3). -->

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list 6 -5 1)))  ; 6 - 5x + x^2
(define factored (sym/factor p))

(print \"p(x) = \" (sym/->string p))
(print \"Factored form: \" (sym/->string factored))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: p(x) = 6 - 5x + x^2, factored form = (x - 2)(x - 3).]

Factoring reveals the roots directly.

---

### 2.8 — Multiplying Polynomials

To multiply two polynomials, distribute every term in the first across every term in the second.

<!-- BUILD: Multiply (x + 2)(x + 3), expand the result. -->

```scheme
(define p1 (sym/poly 'x (list 2 1)))   ; 2 + x
(define p2 (sym/poly 'x (list 3 1)))   ; 3 + x
(define prod (sym/mul p1 p2))
(define expanded (sym/expand prod))

(print \"(x + 2)(x + 3) = \" (sym/->string expanded))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: (x+2)(x+3) = 6 + 5x + x^2.]

Multiplication combines roots multiplicatively.

---

### 2.9 — Adding and Subtracting Polynomials

Add (or subtract) corresponding coefficients.

<!-- BUILD: Add (2x^2 + 3x + 1) + (x^2 - x + 4). -->

```scheme
(define p1 (sym/poly 'x (list 1 3 2)))
(define p2 (sym/poly 'x (list 4 -1 1)))
(define p-sum (sym/add p1 p2))

(print \"p1 = \" (sym/->string p1))
(print \"p2 = \" (sym/->string p2))
(print \"p1 + p2 = \" (sym/->string p-sum))
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: p1 + p2 = 5 + 2x + 3x^2.]

---

### 2.10 — The Degree and Leading Coefficient

The **degree** is the highest power of *x* with a nonzero coefficient. The **leading coefficient** is that coefficient.

<!-- BUILD: Report the degree and leading coefficient of 4x^3 - 2x + 7. -->

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list 7 -2 0 4)))  ; 7 - 2x + 0x^2 + 4x^3
(define deg (sym/degree p))
(define lead (sym/coeff p deg))

(print \"p(x) = \" (sym/->string p))
(print \"Degree: \" deg)
(print \"Leading coefficient: \" lead)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output: degree = 3, leading coefficient = 4.]

---

### 2.11 — End Behavior

The **end behavior** of a polynomial (what happens as *x* → ±∞) is determined by its leading term:

- If the degree is **even** and the leading coefficient is **positive**, both ends go to +∞.
- If even and negative, both ends go to −∞.
- If **odd** and positive, left end → −∞, right end → +∞.
- If odd and negative, left end → +∞, right end → −∞.

<!-- BUILD: Plot a quartic (degree 4) with positive leading coefficient, show both ends rising. -->

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list 1 0 -5 0 1)))  ; 1 - 5x^2 + x^4

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ -3 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 61)))
(define ys (map (lambda (x) (sym/evaluate p x)) xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = x^4 - 5x^2 + 1 (even degree, positive lead)\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: A W-shaped quartic, both ends rising to +∞.]

---

### 2.12 — Turning Points

A polynomial of degree *n* has at most *n*−1 **turning points** (local maxima or minima). These occur where the derivative equals zero.

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = x^3 - 3x (degree 3, so at most 2 turning points). -->

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list 0 -3 0 1)))  ; -3x + x^3

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ -2 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 41)))
(define ys (map (lambda (x) (sym/evaluate p x)) xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = x^3 - 3x (2 turning points)\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Cubic with a local max near x = −1 and a local min near x = 1.]

We'll find the exact turning points with calculus in the next section.

---

### 2.13 — The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra

Every polynomial of degree *n* ≥ 1 has exactly *n* roots in the complex numbers (counting multiplicity). Some may be real, some complex; some may be repeated.

<!-- BUILD: A degree-4 polynomial with 2 real roots and 2 complex roots (e.g., (x^2 - 1)(x^2 + 1) = x^4 - 1). -->

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list -1 0 0 0 1)))  ; x^4 - 1

(print \"p(x) = \" (sym/->string p))
(print \"This factors as (x^2 - 1)(x^2 + 1) = (x-1)(x+1)(x-i)(x+i)\")
(print \"Four roots: 1, -1, i, -i\")
```

[VISUAL: Printed explanation; a plot of y = x^4 − 1 would show it crossing the x-axis at ±1, but the complex roots i and −i are invisible on the real plane.]

---

## III. Rational Functions — Ratios, Asymptotes, and Holes

### History & How It Developed

A **rational function** is a ratio of two polynomials: *f*(*x*) = *P*(*x*)/*Q*(*x*). The Greeks studied ratios of magnitudes (the theory of proportion in Euclid), but the modern theory of rational functions emerged in the 17th and 18th centuries with the calculus, as mathematicians learned to integrate and differentiate these functions and to decompose them via **partial fractions** — a technique that turns every rational function into a sum of simpler pieces.

### Uses & Utility in the World

Rational functions model any system where one quantity is **proportional to the ratio** of two others: the **concentration** of a chemical in a dilution (amount of solute / volume of solution), the **average cost** per item (total cost / number of items), the **intensity** of light at a distance (power / distance²), and the **transfer function** of an electrical filter (output / input). They appear everywhere optimization meets constraints.

### What We'll Cover and Why

We'll learn to recognize the **vertical asymptotes** (where the denominator = 0 and the function blows up), **horizontal asymptotes** (the end behavior), and **holes** (removable singularities where both numerator and denominator vanish). We'll plot them, simplify them, and see how the degrees of the numerator and denominator control the shape.

### Its Utility in the runtime's World

On the canvas, a rational function is a curve with **gaps** (vertical asymptotes) and **limiting heights** (horizontal asymptotes). The runtime uses rational functions for **perspective** (the apparent size of an object is proportional to 1/distance), **fade curves** (a brightness that approaches but never quite reaches zero), and **resonance filters** (audio EQ is built from rational functions in the frequency domain). When you see a curve that shoots to infinity or levels off, it's probably rational.

---

### 3.1 — A Simple Rational Function

Let's plot *f*(*x*) = 1/*x*.

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = 1/x over x in [-5, -0.1] union [0.1, 5]. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x) (/ 1 x)))

(define xs-left (map (lambda (i) (+ -5 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 50)))
(define ys-left (map f xs-left))

(define xs-right (map (lambda (i) (+ 0.1 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 50)))
(define ys-right (map f xs-right))

(plot/with
  (list
    (plot/line xs-left ys-left (list (cons 'label \"left branch\")))
    (plot/line xs-right ys-right (list (cons 'label \"right branch\"))))
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = 1/x (hyperbola)\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Two branches of a hyperbola: left branch in quadrant III (x < 0, y < 0), right branch in quadrant I (x > 0, y > 0), with a vertical asymptote at x = 0 and a horizontal asymptote at y = 0.]

The function is undefined at *x* = 0 (the denominator is zero).

---

### 3.2 — Vertical Asymptote

A **vertical asymptote** occurs at any *x* where the denominator is zero and the numerator is nonzero. The function approaches ±∞ there.

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = 1/(x - 2), which has a vertical asymptote at x = 2. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x) (/ 1 (- x 2))))

(define xs-left (map (lambda (i) (* i 0.1)) (range 0 19)))
(define ys-left (map f xs-left))

(define xs-right (map (lambda (i) (+ 2.1 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 29)))
(define ys-right (map f xs-right))

(plot/with
  (list
    (plot/line xs-left ys-left (list))
    (plot/line xs-right ys-right (list)))
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = 1/(x - 2)\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Two branches with a gap at x = 2; the function shoots to +∞ as x approaches 2 from the right, and to −∞ from the left.]

---

### 3.3 — Horizontal Asymptote

The **horizontal asymptote** is the limiting value as *x* → ±∞. For *P*(*x*)/*Q*(*x*):

- If deg(*P*) < deg(*Q*), the horizontal asymptote is *y* = 0.
- If deg(*P*) = deg(*Q*), it's the ratio of the leading coefficients.
- If deg(*P*) > deg(*Q*), there's no horizontal asymptote (the function grows without bound).

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = (2x + 1)/(x - 3), which has horizontal asymptote y = 2. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x)
            (if (= x 3)
                'nan
                (/ (+ (* 2 x) 1) (- x 3)))))

(define xs (filter (lambda (x) (not (and (> x 2.9) (< x 3.1))))
                   (map (lambda (i) (+ -5 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 101))))
(define ys (map f xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = (2x+1)/(x-3), horizontal asymptote y = 2\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Rational function with vertical asymptote at x = 3, approaching the horizontal line y = 2 as x → ±∞.]

---

### 3.4 — A Hole (Removable Singularity)

If both numerator and denominator share a common factor, canceling it leaves a **hole** — a single point where the function is undefined, but the graph is otherwise continuous.

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = (x^2 - 1)/(x - 1) = (x-1)(x+1)/(x-1), which simplifies to y = x + 1 for x ≠ 1, with a hole at x = 1. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x)
            (if (= x 1)
                'nan
                (/ (- (* x x) 1) (- x 1)))))

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ -2 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 51)))
(define ys (map f xs))

(plot/scatter
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = (x^2-1)/(x-1) = x+1, hole at x=1\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'point-size 2)
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: A line y = x + 1 with a single missing point at (1, 2).]

Algebraically, the function is undefined at *x* = 1; graphically, it's just a line with a pinprick hole.

---

### 3.5 — Slant Asymptote

When deg(numerator) = deg(denominator) + 1, long division gives a **slant asymptote** (an oblique line the curve approaches).

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = (x^2 + 1)/x, which has slant asymptote y = x. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x)
            (if (= x 0)
                'nan
                (/ (+ (* x x) 1) x))))

(define xs-left (map (lambda (i) (+ -5 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 49)))
(define ys-left (map f xs-left))

(define xs-right (map (lambda (i) (+ 0.1 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 49)))
(define ys-right (map f xs-right))

(plot/with
  (list
    (plot/line xs-left ys-left (list))
    (plot/line xs-right ys-right (list))
    (plot/line (list -5 5) (list -5 5) (list (cons 'style \"dashed\") (cons 'label \"y=x\"))))
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = (x^2+1)/x, slant asymptote y=x\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Two branches hugging the line y = x as x → ±∞, with a vertical asymptote at x = 0.]

---

## IV. Radical Functions — Roots and Domains

### History & How It Developed

The **radical** (root) functions — √*x*, ³√*x*, and so on — are the inverse operations of powers. The Babylonians computed square roots four thousand years ago using a geometric-mean algorithm; the general theory of radicals (and the impossibility of solving the quintic by radicals) was one of the great dramas of 19th-century algebra.

### Uses & Utility in the World

Radicals model **inverse-square laws** (intensity ∝ 1/√distance in some contexts), **time-to-fall** under gravity (*t* ∝ √*h*), **standard deviation** (σ = √variance), and **compound interest** (solving for the interest rate involves roots). They are the language of undoing powers.

### What We'll Cover and Why

We'll plot square-root and cube-root functions, understand their **domains** (√*x* is defined only for *x* ≥ 0 in the reals; ³√*x* is defined everywhere), and learn to **compose** them with other functions (e.g., √(*x*² − 1) defines a restricted domain).

### Its Utility in the runtime's World

On the canvas, a radical function is a **gentle curve** — slower-growing than a line. The runtime uses √ for **easing out** (decelerating motion), for **distance fades** (brightness ∝ 1/√distance in some 3D lighting models), and for **harmonic tuning** (the frequency ratio of an equal-tempered semitone is ¹²√2). Radicals tame exponential growth.

---

### 4.1 — The Square Root Function

Let's plot *y* = √*x* for *x* ≥ 0.

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = sqrt(x) over [0, 10]. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x) (sqrt x)))

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (* i 0.1)) (range 0 101)))
(define ys (map f xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = sqrt(x)\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: A gentle curve starting at the origin, rising slowly, concave down.]

The square root is the inverse of squaring (for non-negative numbers).

---

### 4.2 — Domain of the Square Root

In the real numbers, √*x* is defined only when *x* ≥ 0. For *x* < 0, the result is complex.

<!-- BUILD: Attempt to plot sqrt(x) over [-2, 2]; handle the negative domain by marking it undefined. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x)
            (if (< x 0)
                'nan
                (sqrt x))))

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ -2 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 41)))
(define ys (map f xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = sqrt(x), undefined for x < 0\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: The curve appears only for x ≥ 0; the left half of the plot is blank.]

---

### 4.3 — The Cube Root Function

The **cube root** ³√*x* is defined for all real *x* (negative, zero, or positive).

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = cbrt(x) over [-8, 8]. -->

```scheme
(define cbrt (lambda (x)
               (if (< x 0)
                   (- (expt (- x) (/ 1 3)))
                   (expt x (/ 1 3)))))

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ -8 (* i 0.2))) (range 0 81)))
(define ys (map cbrt xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = cbrt(x)\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: An S-shaped curve passing through the origin, rising from bottom-left to top-right.]

The cube root is the inverse of cubing.

---

### 4.4 — A Shifted Square Root

Let's plot *y* = √(*x* − 2), which is √*x* shifted 2 units to the right.

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = sqrt(x - 2) over [2, 12]. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x)
            (if (< x 2)
                'nan
                (sqrt (- x 2)))))

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ 2 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 101)))
(define ys (map f xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = sqrt(x - 2)\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: The square-root curve, starting at (2, 0) instead of (0, 0).]

---

### 4.5 — Composing a Radical with a Polynomial

The function *y* = √(*x*² − 4) has domain *x* ≤ −2 or *x* ≥ 2 (where *x*² − 4 ≥ 0).

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = sqrt(x^2 - 4) over [-5, -2] union [2, 5]. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x)
            (let ((arg (- (* x x) 4)))
              (if (< arg 0)
                  'nan
                  (sqrt arg)))))

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ -5 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 101)))
(define ys (map f xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = sqrt(x^2 - 4)\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: Two branches: one for x ≤ −2, one for x ≥ 2, with a gap in between.]

---

## V. Exponential & Logarithmic Functions — Growth, Decay, and Inverses

### History & How It Developed

The **exponential function** *y* = *a*^*x* (where *a* > 0) is the function of **repeated multiplication**: *a*¹ = *a*, *a*² = *a*·*a*, and so on, extended to all real exponents. The **natural exponential** *e*^*x* (where *e* ≈ 2.71828…) emerges from the study of **compound interest** and **continuous growth**; Euler recognized *e* as the limit (1 + 1/*n*)^*n* as *n* → ∞. The **logarithm** log₍ₐ₎(*x*) is the inverse of *a*^*x*: it asks \"to what power must I raise *a* to get *x*?\" Napier invented logarithms in the early 17th century as a computational aid (turning multiplication into addition), and they were the slide rule's engine for 350 years.

### Uses & Utility in the World

Exponential functions model **population growth** (bacteria double every hour), **radioactive decay** (half-life), **compound interest** (money grows exponentially), and **signal attenuation** (intensity drops exponentially with distance through an absorbing medium). Logarithms measure **orders of magnitude** (the Richter scale for earthquakes, the decibel scale for sound), **information** (entropy in bits), and **complexity** (an algorithm that runs in O(log *n*) time is fast).

### What We'll Cover and Why

We'll plot *y* = 2^*x*, *y* = *e*^*x*, *y* = log₂(*x*), and *y* = ln(*x*). We'll learn the **laws of exponents** and **laws of logarithms**, solve exponential equations (e.g., 2^*x* = 8), and see how exponential growth *explodes* while logarithmic growth *crawls*.

### Its Utility in the runtime's World

On the canvas, exponentials are **J-curves** (rising steeply or falling steeply), and logarithms are **slow climbers**. The runtime uses exponentials for **envelope curves** in audio (attack-decay-sustain-release), for **fade-in/fade-out** (opacity rises/falls exponentially), and for **zoom** (each zoom level is a power of 2). She uses logarithms for **pitch** (musical pitch is logarithmic in frequency: each octave doubles the frequency), for **dynamic range compression** (mapping a wide intensity range into a narrow display range), and for **algorithmic complexity** (a binary search is O(log *n*)). Exponentials and logarithms are the functions of *scaling*.

---

### 5.1 — Plotting y = 2^x

The exponential function *y* = 2^*x* doubles for every unit increase in *x*.

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = 2^x over [-3, 3]. -->

```scheme
(define f (lambda (x) (expt 2 x)))

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (+ -3 (* i 0.1))) (range 0 61)))
(define ys (map f xs))

(plot/line
  xs
  ys
  (list
    (cons 'title \"y = 2^x\")
    (cons 'xlabel \"x\")
    (cons 'ylabel \"y\")
    (cons 'grid #t)))
```

[VISUAL: A J-shaped curve passing through (0, 1), rising steeply for x > 0, approaching 0 as x → −∞.]

Exponential growth is **explosive**.

---

### 5.2 — The Natural Exponential e^x

The **natural exponential** *e*^*x* is the exponential with base *e* ≈ 2.71828… It's the function whose derivative is itself.

<!-- BUILD: Plot y = e^x over [-2, 2]. -->
")
